Multiple ways of abstraction:

Infra/crosschain: L0s

Liquidity: bridges (L0s)

Wallets: abstracted wallets

Discovery: dApp stores

What you can take away is that web2 games are doing a great job at abstracting away the technicalities of onchain transactions within their games.

This level of abstraction should also be put into every vertical in crypto (defi)

So when users filter down, it'll be natural.

Starting to see a bunch of web2 gaming studios deploying to web3 (esp in Korea).

Not much talk about it in the space but it's the easiest way to onboard and keep users transacting onchain.

The next 100mm people onchain will probably be skewed towards games, not lending apps.

In conclusion: build your edge (tbh it's always evolving) and lean in on others who have edge in different places.

Understand that markets are always right and trying to adhere towards trends is always higher EV than arguing about why price isn't going up/down online.

GN.

The greatest and worst thing about crypto is the community.

Best part is being able to speak with ppl who have a great understanding on mkt dynamics to lean on.

Worst part is that everyone has an opinion and the noise is blinding.

Small circle > large circle.

Your goal as a speculator in the markets is to understand what's priced in and what's not and assign probabilities accordingly.

That understanding is "edge".

It's not easy but it gives you a framework for how you define risk.

Most don't realize that you need both fundamental analysis and market dynamics to survive the crypto markets.

New developments, good tech, tokenomics, etc. are all great fundamental principles to understand but they only serve as catalysts for market dynamics.

Price has the biggest psychological impact on participants.

When prices go up, people fomo in. "Maybe this really is the bottom".

When this happens and a slight increase in liquidity appears in the market who do you think takes that opportunity to unload?

Thoughts :)

For the participants who are still buying/selling are they buying to hold or buying to sell higher?

Are funds buying to sell higher or buying to hold?

There are few participants in the market right now. Pumps won't come without dumps.

I see the same onchain alts being shilled on twitter right now but looks like just a few entities buying tokens.

If markets get sour again and dry up even more do they sell or do they buy more?

Frameworks to keep in mind:

1) Who are the current buyers/sellers?
2) Are they marginal buyers/sellers?
3) Is there sustained demand/supply?
4) Are you desperate for prices to go up/down?

Again, these are personal lessons and might not apply to any of you.

GN.

6. Patience is a position

There is always buzz in the market and always something flashy and new. I've gotten chopped up chasing rotations and getting in too late. Patience to wait for a critical point in the market (large dump in a clear uptrend) to go risk on = positioning.

5. Denominate in strength

I'm not a fan of diversification (within the same segment of the market). Find the market winners and denominate in that (ex. ETH). If what you're trading/buying can't outperform the winners why bother? Let the weak go, double down on the winners.

4. Build your network

Crypto is a community at the heart and there's so much going on you can't capture it all. Build a network where you can bounce ideas, see what's going on in different parts of the market, and help each other out. No one is better than the next.

3. Bigger, fewer bets

One thing I wish I did was hammering larger high conviction trades instead of spreading thin to "capture" the entire market. Luckily I did this decently well with avax but could've done much better through the years.

2. Narratives run the market

Most of everything you see on twitter or elsewhere is simply info to either formulate or corroborate a thesis. The trick is to figure out which are strong, which last, and which to not consider.

1. Stubbornness is not conviction

In the beginning of the run I was an ETH maxi and since all of defi was focused on ETH that's where my loyalty laid. When I heard of Luna, Avalanche, Solana, and  other layer 1s very early on, I was closed minded and passed at single digits.

A few lessons I learned from this run.

I'll keep this short, since this is more of an internal dialogue with myself and not a preachy message to you all.

It sounds pretty simple but trading psychology matters a lot. It's not just technicals and lines.

You can be right about a direction or a trade setup but execution is a mix of technical + mental.

This is why leverage is hard for most. It adds too much mental stress.

I think one of the biggest mistakes most make when trading is having a high timeframe bias and using that to trade on low timeframes.

Just because you're bullish on a higher timeframe doesn't mean you long/buy at resistance and vice versa if you're bearish.

veTokenomics is a lockup + incentivized model where users have to lockup capital to get a boosted incentive for the core feature of a protocol.

is that core feature worth locking up tokens for 1-4yrs?

for most protocols, no.

secondly, now users have to worry about the PA of it

Secondly, projects should focus on growing demand for the actual project itself instead of scheming a new tokenomic model to try and artificially create demand.

veTokenomics is a prime example imo. Works well with certain projects, but not most.

here's my quick take on it:

In a raging bull run tokenomic models imo are just used to create a narrative (token burns, lockup models, etc.) to draw attention.

Tokenomics matter, but the newest model is not always the best.

Focus on tokenomics that bring value to the token, not to pump the price of it.

Projects should focus less on designing less ponzimonic models for tokens and more on finding ways to increase protocol revenue.

10. Big picture

You're:
>> earning deposit interests on Aave
>> earning borrow interests on Aave
>> earning deposit interests on Curve
>> compounding on Aave and Curve
>> becoming a farmer

9. Compounding

Now in DeFi, you get rewards instantaneously so you can claim your Matic at any time.

You can either:
a) add Matic to the matic pool on AAVE and earn an additional 8% on that.

b) swap for more stables and rinse and repeat

Fees are pennies on Matic!

8. CRV (curve) rewards

You can now deposit the 20k USDT into @CurveFinance's platform and earn 6.75% in USDT + 26% APY in Matic!

Yes, over 30%+ APY on your loan from CRV + the borrow interest you're already earning on AAVE.

Now we're really putting your money to work. https://t.co/ewjWBdRtB8

7. cont.

Now, because I deposited more into the USDT pool the interest earned from my deposits will easily cover the interest needed to pay for the 20k USDT loan.

So what do you do with the 20k USDT loan you just took out?

It gets even crazier.

6. My borrow strategy

Let's say I deposit 20k into DAI, 20k into USDC, and 60k into USDT pools.

I have 40k as collateral where I can borrow ~20k USDT.

I'm earning interest on 20k DAI, 20k USDC and  *80k* USDT.

Instead of putting 100k to work, I'm using 120k now.

5. Why Borrow?

Don't forget when you deposit as collateral you also earn.

For USDT you earn 10% + 13% APY to deposit.

You pay 12.28% and earn 14.53% APY to borrow.

You're essentially getting paid a lot of Matic tokens to borrow on top of deposit.

4. Borrow earnings

>> the variable borrow APY is the interest YOU have to pay additional to your loan
>> the Matic % underneath is what Aave will pay YOU just to borrow
>> for USDT you can earn 14.53% APY in Matic just by borrowing (you have to pay 12.33% APY however) https://t.co/AUne93GRZS

3. Deposit yield

>> just by depositing you can earn 4-23% APY
>> you earn 3-10% APY in native stablecoin + 3-13% in Matic rewards
>> I think Matic allocated like 40-50M in rewards for these Aave pools
>> without borrowing you'll earn these rewards in real time! https://t.co/tAWSjvVHVV

2. Use @AaveAave to deposit funds on Matic

>> deposit stables
>> DAI and USDC are used for collateral
>> USDT cannot be collateralized but earns most deposit yield
>> you'll see why depositing into the USDT pool is advantageous even if you can't collateralize

1. Bridge funds over to Matic

>> use their native wallet dApp
>> bridge some Matic (for fees)
>> bridge your stables (USDT, USDC, DAI)
>> takes roughly ~10 min in total

7. Governance token

$BAG is the protocol's governance token in charge of making decisions and incentivizing users to interact with the protocol.

Added bonus is that $BAG is "supported by the real fiat liquidity gained by collateral of the stablecoin".

6. Stablecoin

$USDap is the protocol's stablecoin which is pegged to $1 by pulling from several bonds with different terms, rates, and exp dates.

Bonds are old and relatively stable even in volatile environments.

The stablecoin is only issued with sufficient collateral in USD.

5. Off-chain protocols

- Traditional security accounting systems will be used for collateral locking

- Off-chain banks and brokerage accounts to settle securities and fiat interaction

- Usage of Bloomberg terminal and other pricing sources to interact with price oracles

4. On-chain protocols

- Using in house price and security oracle and open-source governance from Compound

- This price oracle will be used to derive accounts and prices from custody accounts off-chain where the collateral is being held

10. Confirm and Swap!

So once you submit your fee, the transaction will be sent to validate!

Congrats you have now used a DEX! https://t.co/zyeJhQeTfb

9. Fees!

Ok this is the worst part of defi currently.

This is why L2 (layer-2 solutions exist).

The ETH network is slow and expensive.

To transact you have to pay fees.

It's the price you pay to access all of defi :)

Click "edit" for gas fee.

Click "fast" and save. https://t.co/Q2bBSwHhwS

8d. Don't trust anything but official sources

Never trust any person or account that is posting contracts.

They can easily create a fake address and have you send money to them.

Only trust a project's official tweets or website info.

Coingecko is pretty reliable as well.

8c. Token not found

If you type in the token but you can't see it on Uniswap, try this.

Find the official token addresses on the project's official website or twitter or coingecko (photo below)

Click on the copy icon next to the contract on coingecko.

Paste into Uni! https://t.co/Bq2P8JpiqT

8b. Liquidity

If the token you want to swap to has no liquidity the "Price Impact" will be very high.

This means no one is providing liquidity for the swap so try checking on other platforms like sushiswap! https://t.co/OxgDNUFwMr

8. Swapping

Ok so now you should see that you can swap "from" a token "to" another one.

Click ETH for the "from".

And search up the token you want to swap to!

Then enter how much ETH you want to use to swap!

If price impact is high, then there might not be enough liquidity! https://t.co/BwtIhUKfiE

7. Connect Metamask to Uniswap

Go to https://t.co/KrFzpZaV8K

Click the "connect" button in the corner.

Then click metamask!

It will ask for viewing permissions.

Accept! Your wallet is connected to Uniswap.

This is how we'll connect metamask to all other web apps as well! https://t.co/um3nDJ80Z5

6. Uniswap

Ok so Uniswap is what is called a 'DEX' or decentralized exchange.

It allows you to swap one eth token for another eth token on demand.

No need to wait for order flows and fills.

Say I want to exchange $ETH for $VSP or $SHOPX.

Uniswap is the way.

But fees!

5. Fill your new wallet up

Send your ETH from coinbase to your new wallet!

Hint: you can click on your account name on metamask to copy your public wallet address.

Send funds there and wait!

Metamask will update in real time once it receives the funds! https://t.co/GW6mxSEfC5

4. Adding ledger to metamask

(skip if you don't have a ledger)

Metamask allows you to add your physical ledger to metamask.

Do this for extra security.

Any transaction will require you to approve transactions using your physical ledger.

3. Connect with metamask

Metamask is a chrome extension that connects you to almost every decentralized app on the web.

Install + create an account and write down your seed phrase (never save on any cloud network...write it down)

Congrats you now have your own wallet.

2. Why a physical ledger?

A physical ledger offers security when transacting/holding crypto.

It's your own "physical" wallet.

In order to transact with defi apps, it requires physical confirmation for transactions.

And a bunch of other security advantages, DYOR :)

1. Acquire ETH or USDC

In order to interact with decentralized exchanges you need your own wallet.

Let's say you have ETH on Coinbase.

Two options:

1. Send eth from coinbase to ledger -> connect to metamask

2. Create a metamask wallet -> send eth from coinbase to metamask

9. Sales call

No matter what service you're offering, the sales call should not sound like you're selling that service.

You are a doctor diagnosing a patient.

If you see fit for a prescription, then and only then do you offer a solution.

Dive deep into their practices.

6. PRACTICE

Grab your buddy.
Practice your calls over and over.

Start to move away from scripts.
Become natural at objection handling.

Think about how adding value handles objections.
Close more confidently.

BOOM.

Prepare follow up beforehand

>> open your calendar
>> mark 3 times in the next week that you're free

In the call when you mention a follow up, suggest those times immediately.

Get a date settled, so you sound confident and prepared.

Leave them with a strong impression.

5. Close / followup

If they're a 7+, you can close the deal.

Handle a few more objections.
Affirm with conviction.
GIVE MORE VALUE.

If they're a 6 or below, schedule a follow up.

Here's something you should always do before any call regarding your follow up.

This is by far one of the best ways to grasp where exactly your prospect is in the pipeline.

Most people leave the sales call without knowing where their prospect stands.

If you have to guess where they're at after the call, you're doing it wrong.

4. The 1-10 scale method

This next part is super important.

1 = 99% discount and still won't sign on
10 = send the invoice right now

You need to figure out where they stand right now from 1-10 on this scale.

This will help you close right now or in your follow up.

If their issue is with pricing don't respond with "hmm let's see if we can work it out."

Instead be very confident in your response.

"Here's exactly why we price our service like this..."

The moment you give in you start to lose control.

THEY CAN FEEL THAT.

3. Address real objection

You've unraveled their actual objection now.

Your goal is to affirm exactly why this objections is really not an objection.

Have CONVICTION  in your response.

Without it, they won't be convinced.

Game time.

2. Dive deep

When they say "I need more time", they really just mean

I DON'T KNOW ABOUT THIS.

Your goal is to figure out what THIS is.

Is it Pricing?
>> what about the pricing?
>> is it how it's structured?
>> is it the value?
>> is it too expensive?

GO DEEP (or go home).

1. Affirm + Redirect

Affirm that their response is normal.

Then, go straight into asking exactly what they need more time to think about.

Without this, you'll be helpless in ANY followup.

Don't be afraid to push to get this answered.

"Awesome so what's holding you back?"

6. Be confident and direct

Every thinks that to sound not like a salesperson you have to be very conversational and friendly.

How would Jake's friend try to go through the receptionist?

5. "What is the purpose of the call?"

"I'm here to speak with Jake. It's Matt from Paik Capital. He should know what this call is about."

At the very least, this gets the receptionist to go to the business owner and explain the call.

There's a good chance he picks up.

Redirecting the question is the best way to push through this objection.

The receptionist now has to answer your question, taking the focus away from her question.

It also shows that you aren't nervous about who you are which most sales people tend to be.

Confidence works.

4. The Art of Redirection

You lowered the chance of objections.

You might still get some.

Handle them like a boss.

"May I ask who's calling?

"Yes it's Matt from Paik Capital. Is Jake in right now?"

Flip the script.
Take control.
Redirect the question.

Why does the first one work?

In the receptionist's mind it shows that you have some sort of connection with the business owner.

Only strangers use full names when addressing people.

Secondly, being direct helps with urgency and also gets rid of the "salesy" type of vibe.

3. Respond with ONLY first names

"Hey Sarah, it's Matt. Can you put me through to Jake?"

Let's compare that to what a typical sales person would say:

"Hey Sarah, my name is Matthew Paik from Paik Capital. I was wondering if Jake Roberts was in the office?"

Not good.

2. The Opening

The opening is where the receptionist will introduce herself and the company.

"Hello this is XYZ company, it's Sarah speaking how may I help you?"

PERFECT.

Take note of her first name.

This is key.

Secondly, only call leads where you know their name.

5. Outreach like crazy

>> twitter DM
>> IG video DM
>> FB messenger

4. Define your service

So by now you realize you're going to pitch content creation to businesses.

How many posts a day will you be able to provide for brands?

What type of brands do you want to work with?

Why is content creation important and how does it affect direct ROI?

The test:

Give them a few sample brand accounts.

Have them recreate 3-6 posts each.

See how they do.

They won't be perfect, but they can always improve based on your feedback.

Hire 2-3 that you like.

There's your content creation team.

3. Hire VAs

I like Upwork

>> Find content designers VAs
>> Filter for $5-10/hr
>> Get them all on a video call with you
>> Explain your repeatable process of content creation
>> Send your swipe file to them
>> Give them a test (read next)

You won't make good content initially.

Unless you're a designer.

Then you probably don't need to practice much.

Focus on a theme and style.

Simplify the process.

MAKE IT REPEATABLE.

This is important.

2. Practice. Practice. Practice.

>> Find a small brand on IG
>> Screenshot a row of their posts
>> Go to Canva
>> Recreate the images to make them BETTER
>> Use your swipe file as inspiration
>> Do this over and over with diff posts
>> Keep the styles consistent

This part is about creating a swipe file of posts and grids that work well.

Saving these screenshots into a folder is what is called a "swipe file".

Build this up for ideas and inspirations later on.

Without doing market research you're shooting in the dark.

Direct response copywriting is needed in every industry and business.

It's used for ads, blogs, landing pages, funnels, and so much more.

If you want to learn more and be able to start writing compelling copy, it's going to take months.

Not weeks.

But there is good news:

1. Think of the end goal action

2. Write down my initial thoughts (even if it's wordy, long, and terrible)

3. Cut it down / make it concise

4. Add in appropriate adverbs and adjectives that add the emotional effect to it

5. Read it over out loud 10x

6. Repeat again and again

Tip 3: Practice every day

>> Go on Facebook or google
>> Find article headlines
>> Find ad headlines

>> Write them down
>> Now write your version next to it

Do this every day.

Tip 2: Realize the emotion

Excellent copywriting plays off of your emotions.

Power words, trigger words, etc.

"Alarming"
"Shocking"
"Unexpected"

These will have you locked in to that sentence, forcing you to read the rest.

Understand this.
Take it in.

>> What ads did you click on recently

Study the headlines.

Now keep these in mind next time you start writing some copy for a client or for yourself.

Utilize these three concepts to rip through barriers and appeal to your audience.

These three will get you RESULTS.

3. Level of understanding and skepticism

How well do they think your product/service and others work?

Rank it on a scale of 1-10.

Closer to 10 -> address the doubts

Closer to 1 -> focus on why "you"
(no doubt means you're just convincing them to choose you)

If heavily exposed to competitors and other solutions, focus on a competitive edge that directly alleviates or benefits them.

Include numbers, case studies, and direct correlations.

If less exposed, focus on clarity.

How exactly can you alleviate or benefit them?

2. Exposure to similar solutions/products

Craft your copy according to how much the audience knows about how similar solutions/products can satisfy their desires.

Your copy needs to be in context to what your audience understands.

Irrelevant info is a waste of words and space.

Here, the most powerful feeling is their desire to get rid of their constant back pain.

Your copy will appeal and focus on this desire.

It's not-- why your product/service is awesome.

It's -- how your product answers their mass desire.

Alleviation and benefits.

Not features.

1. Mass desire

You're working with a chiropractor client.

Find the most IMPACTFUL feeling their audience has.

Fear
"What if I don't get my sore back checked out?"

Desire
"Get rid of my constant back pain"

Curiosity
"Would monthly visits really help?"

Which is most POWERFUL?

First of all, thoroughly understand your client's audience or your audience.

Their fears, desires, and curiosities.

Craft their prototype customer in extraordinary detail.

What does the typical person in their niche look like?

Complete that then move on.

This is literally every step I took (except making the business official) to get real results!

6. Streamline the process

Ok, so now you've gotten 8-10 sales.

Took a lot of work and probably a few weeks to hammer through.

Now, streamline the communication between clients and contractors.

Then hire someone to manage the whole workflow.

Boom.

5. Get clients

Use every social media platform.

Go to business pages, check out their designs, and create mockups for them.

They'll be interested.

Give them your pitch.

Too much work?

Run Facebook ads.

Won't explain that here, but it works.

4. Make things official

- Website
- LLC
- FB page
- Logo

This thread has everything you need to do for this step:

https://t.co/OFn4576LSK

3. Create your offers

Talk with your small network and get their prices.

Now double or triple that price and that's the price you'll charge clients.

So if your contractors want $30/logo charge $90-100.

You keep the $60-70 difference.

Nice margins :)

2. (continued)

Pick a few of them to work with you.

Tell them you'll need them for lots of clients.

Ask for their portfolios and samples.

Cool, now you have on demand contractors, multiple portfolios to use, and an idea of how to fulfill orders.

2. Build a small network

Ok, you might have a few friends who can do this stuff.

Ask if they want to join as contractors for you.

Don't have any?

Go to Fiverr.

Find 10-20 ppl who can do your service.

Message all of them with a business proposal.

1. Choose a service

What does your media agency specialize in?

Choose 1 or 2 things, not 5-10.
- Logo creation
- Logo animation
- Ad video creation
- Ad graphic creation
- etc.

Don't be the jack of all trades agency; focus on just a few services.

3. Speak "their" language

Will a Japanese person understand my Korean?

Probably not. (well...maybe)

How does your audience speak?

How do they think?

Figure that out.

Learn their style.

Then put it into words.

Now you're speaking with them, not to them.

2. Think of the individual

Your focus should be on an individual archetype, not on millions of people.

If you're focusing on accountants, think of just one.

Go extremely deep with it.

Your copy is really aimed at only one person, repeated a million times.

1. Not about being creative

Your copy should invoke an emotion produced by its readers but decided by you.

And unless you want people to just have an "oh that was clever lol" attitude you should prob change it.

Figure out how you want your audience to feel.

It was already created (since everyone sells the same thing).

You just had to get traffic to your affiliate link.

Sounded genius to me at the time.

But anyway...

Here's the biggest takeaway:

It was affiliate marketing for a pyramid scheme.

So once you bought, you get a unique link to the beginning of the funnel sequence.

Then that unique link pushes your affiliate code through the whole funnel.

I mean the funnel was so powerful and unique...

So basically I got played.

But man the marketing and systems "BIM" had in place still amazes me to this day.

I mean his funnel was a masterful combination of email and video marketing.

3 webinars all spaced out 24 hours from each other.

Somehow I did, and boom just like that purchased.

The rest is history.

I found out that the whole point of learning sales and online marketing was to sell someone else the program. 

Every 8th sale goes to the person who's ad I clicked on to for the funnel.

In the last video is where Vick tells you about the offer which sounds amazing.

It's $997 and you only have "24 minutes" to purchase or else you lose the chance FOREVER.

How could I not use all my negotiation skills to convince my dad to buy this for me.

Now the webinar ends with another invitation to his 2nd webinar.

Watched it.

Still no mention of him selling anything to me.

Just another invitation to his final webinar.

I'm already 1000% sold.

I want to be that high school kid making $200,000/mo.

How can this be a scam?

He's teaching me for FREE how to get people to visit my blog, how to run ads, and how to get people's attention.

Awesome.

The only issue was that some of his tools he was demoing for us were "proprietary" to the business.

I sign up immediately and I'm sent a link 60 minutes later telling me to sign up quickly for his limited live webinar.

Of course it's not actually live but prerecorded.

I watch eagerly as he speaks.

He actually did give decent points about online traffic...

This is how I fell for their trap.

I watched as Vick (the head) was speaking about his lifestyle and how his system led him to make $200,000/mo.

He then tells you to sign up for his webinar where he "explains" how he got there.

So far nothing wrong...

"BIM" or Big Idea Mastermind was essentially a huge pyramid scheme.

There were three tiers of services you could buy (forgot the names).

The cheapest was $997 then $2497 then like $5000.

This is not revealed by the ad.

In fact it's not shown for 3 days.

But you need lots of collateral which is why Credit Spreads are amazing.

Essentially, it's selling premium while providing the collateral upfront in a cheaper way.

This limits the gains, but minimizes the downside.

https://t.co/xAKinGDlYW

For example:
I sold a contract to someone for $1.50 that expires next week.

Fast forward to the end of the week and the contract is not ITM:

- That $1.50 contact is worth now $0.10 since it is basically worthless.
- I collect the difference of $1.40 on the contract = $140.

Selling premium is a strategy that makes you the "bank".

- Have your options lost value?
- It goes to the person who sold it to you!
- That's what selling premium is. You sell the contract and as time decay eats away the value, you inherit it!
- You need collateral (bad).
üëá

Contracts that expire in 1-4 weeks are heavily exposed to theta time decay.

This reduces the contract value in an option as the expiration date approaches.

This decay ACCELERATES as the expiration date approaches.

But, the more time you have on your contract, the less decay! https://t.co/oZoz1YFuWH

Most people see TIME going against them in Options trading.

Here are 3 ways to use time on your side:
- Far out contracts (not weekly, but 3 months or more)
- Selling Premium
- Credit Spreads

By looking at both the HTF and LTF, you will see the grander picture!

- The hash of that specific block would change, requiring the next block to update that value in its own block.

- Doing this would again change its own hash since the data in that block was altered

- This repeats for every block after. 

Not feasible. 

Blockchain is immutable.

Why hash?

- A hash is generated by a fn that converts data to a mix of letters and numbers. Any change to the data changes the hash.

- Every block contains both the hash of its own block and the previous block for security.

- What happens if I alter one block‚Äôs data?

Pt. 2

- The blockchain is then updated on every node (computer)

- Changing the blockchain would require you to change the majority of the nodes on the network (would take immense computing power)!

- The infamous 51% attack comes from this concept!

Block  ‚û°Ô∏è chain 

- The network consists of computers (nodes) that each hold a copy of the blockchain

- A transaction occurs, validated by nodes that check all the details!

- Once verified, it‚Äôs stored as a block given a unique hash

- Finally, the block is added to the chain

What is it:

- A distributed ledger or in simple terms, a decentralized database

- Block = digital information to be stored

- Chain = the ledger holding the info
